<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><img src="http://route50.net/data/gallery/submissions/3391_full.png" alt=""></p>
<p>In a <a href="http://koaning.io/pokemon-recommendations.html">previous</a> document I've explained how to use the CAPM model to create naive ranking for pokemon. Even though the approach had some logic to it, I wanted to explore if a naive <a href="http://koaning.io/mini-trueskill-demo.html">probibalistic implementation</a> of trueskill could do the job as well. This document contains a python implementation my naive approach as well as an application to a pokemon dataset. The first part will explain how it is made and tested. The second part will analyse the ranking of all 750 pokemon.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Starting-Data">Starting Data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Starting-Data"></a></h2><p>Before writing any application code, it seems sensible to first think about how to test if the code works. It would be a good idea to simulate some random players with predetermined skill levels such that we can test if our ranking algorithm can at least rank simulated data well enough. The code below generates this data.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">uuid</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">numpy</span> <span class="kn">as</span> <span class="nn">np</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="kn">as</span> <span class="nn">pd</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">json</span> 
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="kn">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="o">%</span><span class="k">matplotlib</span> inline  
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">seaborn</span><span class="p">;</span> <span class="n">seaborn</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="n">SIZE_ARR</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">100</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">sim</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">p2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">entropy</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot; </span>
<span class="sd">    Given two players (tuples: &lt;name, skill&gt;) simulate </span>
<span class="sd">    a game between them. Returns (winner-name, loser-name)</span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="n">r</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">randint</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="n">entropy</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">entropy</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">p1</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">r</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">p2</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">p1</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">p2</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">p2</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">p1</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>    

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">gen_data</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_users</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n_games</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">100</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">entropy</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Generate a lot of games and outputs a list of user tuples</span>
<span class="sd">    (&lt;name&gt;, &lt;skill&gt;)as well as a list of games played.</span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="n">data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>
    <span class="n">users</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[(</span><span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">uuid</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">uuid4</span><span class="p">())[:</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">i</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_users</span><span class="p">)]</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">_</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_games</span><span class="p">):</span> 
        <span class="n">i</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">j</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">choice</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">users</span><span class="p">)),</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="n">u1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">u2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">users</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">users</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">j</span><span class="p">]</span> 
        <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">sim</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">u1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">u2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">entropy</span><span class="p">))</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">users</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;winner&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;loser&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Code-that-does-the-math">Code that does the math<a class="anchor-link" href="#Code-that-does-the-math"></a></h1><p>We'll now concern ourselves with writing code that updates a system of beliefs. The belief will be captured in a numpy array and can be interpreted as a histogram of likelihood values for a certain level of skill. The algorithm is explained in the <a href="http://koaning.io/pokemon-recommendations.html">previous blogpost</a> as well but schematically, this is what the belief update looks like;</p>
<p><img src="http://i.imgur.com/Q9T5V8M.png" alt=""></p>
<p>We start out with two arrays of prior skill beliefs for player 1 and player 2. We then combine them in a two dimensional density. This is our prior belief of the skill levels of the two players. Once a player wins, we can update this belief. One player has a lower skill level. To translate this to our belief system, we cut away all likelihood in the triangle of the losing player. Then we marginalise our belief back to the two players. By repeating this for all the games, we hope to achieve a belief of skill that can be updated in real time.</p>
<h2 id="Towards-Code">Towards Code<a class="anchor-link" href="#Towards-Code"></a></h2><p>Next we'll define all the functions that do the ranking. These functions are meant to be minimal, as we only want to check if this algorithm can work. It makes sense to think about what our app code might look like and to think about how to test individual components before writing the code though. I'm not particularily religious about testing but I do see some value for writing a test before writing code here. We're going to be munging with numpy matrices and typos in indices will be unforgiving.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

<pre><code>p1 = np.array([1.,2.,3.])
p2 = np.array([3.,2.,1.])
p3 = np.array([1.,1.,1.])
mat1 = gen_prior(p1, p2)
mat2 = gen_prior(p2, p1)
mat3 = gen_prior(p3, p3)
m1, m2 = gen_marginals(mat1)
m3, m4 = gen_marginals(mat2)
np1, np2 = gen_marginals(cut_matrix(mat1))

assert all(m1 == m2[::-1]) #marginals should still be same shape 
assert all(m3 == m4[::-1]) #marginals should still be same shape 
assert np.sum(mat1) == np.sum(mat2) #matrices should have equal values
assert np.sum(mat3) == 9 #all ones should sum to 9 
assert all(np1 == np2[::-1]) #marginals should still be same shape</code></pre>
<p>With these tests in place, I could worry about the code.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">get_player_stats</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">name</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Check if a player exists in the dictionary. If not, add it. </span>
<span class="sd">    Then returns the player belief. </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">name</span> <span class="ow">not</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">d</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">keys</span><span class="p">():</span> 
        <span class="n">d</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">name</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ones</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">SIZE_ARR</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ones</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">SIZE_ARR</span><span class="p">))</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">d</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">name</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">gen_prior</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">arr1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">arr2</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Combines two arrays into a matrix.</span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">matrix</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">arr1</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">matrix</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">arr2</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">cut_matrix</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mat</span><span class="p">):</span> 
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Cuts the matrix according to likelihood update rule. </span>
<span class="sd">    Also applies normalisation</span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="n">posterior</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">triu</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mat</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mf">0.000001</span>
    <span class="n">posterior</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">posterior</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">posterior</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">posterior</span>
    
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">gen_marginals</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">posterior_mat</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    From a cut matrix, generate the appropriate marginals back</span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="n">winner</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">squeeze</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">asarray</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">posterior_mat</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)))</span>
    <span class="n">loser</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">squeeze</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">asarray</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">posterior_mat</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)))</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">winner</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">loser</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">update</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">winner</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">loser</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Given a winner and user, update our state. </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="n">winner_arr</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">get_player_stats</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">winner</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">loser_arr</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">get_player_stats</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">loser</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">prior_mat</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">gen_prior</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">loser_arr</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">winner_arr</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">posterior_mat</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">cut_matrix</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prior_mat</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">new_winner</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">new_loser</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">gen_marginals</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">posterior_mat</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">d</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">loser</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">new_loser</span>
    <span class="n">d</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">winner</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">new_winner</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>I wrote the code and the tests passed. For now this is enough. Before running this code against the pokemon dataset, let us first run it against some simulated data.</p>
<h2 id="Running-the-code-a-few-times.">Running the code a few times.<a class="anchor-link" href="#Running-the-code-a-few-times."></a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">plot_scores</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">plot_idx</span><span class="p">):</span> 
    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">plot_idx</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">scatter</span><span class="p">(</span>
        <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">users</span><span class="p">)),</span> 
        <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">d</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">usr</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]]</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">SIZE_ARR</span><span class="p">))</span> <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">usr</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">users</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="p">)</span>
    
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">plot_dist</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">plot_idx</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">plot_idx</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">usr</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">users</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">SIZE_ARR</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">d</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">usr</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]],</span> <span class="n">alpha</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">0.5</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Simulate-n_players-=-100,-n_games-=-400,-entropy-=-1">Simulate <code>n_players</code> = 100, <code>n_games</code> = 400, <code>entropy</code> = 1<a class="anchor-link" href="#Simulate-n_players-=-100,-n_games-=-400,-entropy-=-1"></a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">d</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">{}</span> 
<span class="n">users</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">gen_data</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_users</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">100</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n_games</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">400</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">entropy</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">json</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loads</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_json</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">orient</span> <span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;records&#39;</span><span class="p">)):</span> 
    <span class="n">update</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;winner&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">i</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;loser&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>
    
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">plot_scores</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">221</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plot_dist</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">222</span><span class="p">)</span>

<h2 id="Simulate-n_players-=-100,-n_games-=-400/10000,-entropy-=-15">Simulate <code>n_players</code> = 100, <code>n_games</code> = 400/10000, <code>entropy</code> = 15<a class="anchor-link" href="#Simulate-n_players-=-100,-n_games-=-400/10000,-entropy-=-15"></a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Increasing the entropy in the system will cause the ranking algorithm to measure the noise more than the signal, but more games allow for convergence to still occur.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">d</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">{}</span> 
<span class="n">users</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">gen_data</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_users</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">100</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n_games</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">400</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">entropy</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">json</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loads</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_json</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">orient</span> <span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;records&#39;</span><span class="p">)):</span> 
    <span class="n">update</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;winner&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">i</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;loser&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">plot_scores</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">221</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plot_dist</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">222</span><span class="p">)</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>There's still some room for improvement to this system to make the convergence better, but it seems well enough for my purposes. I want to use this metric to rank pokemon so if I need to simulate some more outcomes between two pokemon then I won't mind. For more real-time purposes, the following tweaks seem to be important;</p>
<ul>
<li>New matches are allocated randomly, which is suboptimal from a learning perspective. If you want to fine tune the top 10 players it makes sense to have them play against eachother if you are unsure who is number 1. If instead you'd have one of these players compete against somebody mediocre you can predict the game outcome before it even started. This means you would not learn anything from that game. </li>
<li>I am using buckets to simulate a distribution for a player. It may be better to use Beta distributions instead and save it's parameters. This would make the blogpost harder to read for more novice readers which is the main reason of not doing it, but this should improve the stability and remove the need for the hard coded smoothing parameter in the <code>cut_matrix</code> function. </li>
</ul>
<p>For the pokemon dataset I only have one concern; the effect of rock paper scissors.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Pokemon-Data">Pokemon Data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Pokemon-Data"></a></h1><p>I took the liberty of preparing a dataset. It's easy to do yourself with a bit of python and <a href="https://github.com/phalt/pykemon">this</a> project. I'll use the formula from my previous <a href="http://koaning.io/pokemon-recommendations.html">post</a> here again to create a function that can simulate the outcome of a pokemon battle. It will be based on the number of turns that one pokemon can outlast the other.</p>
$$ T_{ij} = \frac{HP_i}{DMG_{ji}} $$<p></p>
<p>where $T_{ij}$ is the number of turns the pokemon $i$ would be able to survive the opponent $j$ if it were to be attacked indefinately, $HP_i$ is the amount of hitpoints that pokemon $i$ has and $DMG_ji$ is the amount of damage a basic attack pokemon $j$ would deal to pokemon $i$. This damage is defined via:</p>
$$ DMG_{ji} = \frac{2L_j+10}{250} \times \frac{A_j}{D_i} \times w_{ji}$$<p></p>
<p>The situation will very much assume some core aspects of the game away. The hope is that my making this assumption we'll still leave much of the actual pokemon game intact.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">poke_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;http://koaning.io/theme/data/full_pokemon.csv&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">weak_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;http://koaning.io/theme/data/pokemon_weakness.csv&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">poke_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>



<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">weakness_weight</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">types_j</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">types_i</span><span class="p">):</span> 
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Returns w_{ji} </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="n">res</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">1.</span>
    <span class="n">possible_types</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">t</span> <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">t</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">weak_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;type&#39;</span><span class="p">]]</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">filter</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="k">lambda</span> <span class="n">t</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">t</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">possible_types</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">types_i</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">j</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">filter</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="k">lambda</span> <span class="n">t</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">t</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">possible_types</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">types_j</span><span class="p">):</span>
            <span class="n">res</span> <span class="o">*=</span> <span class="nb">float</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">weak_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">weak_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;type&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="n">j</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">])</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">res</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">calc_tij</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">poke_i</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poke_j</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Calculate the number of turns one pokemon would outlast the other. </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="n">poke_row_i</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poke_row_j</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">poke_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">poke_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;name&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="n">poke_i</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">poke_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">poke_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;name&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="n">poke_j</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">dmg_ji</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">200.</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="mi">250</span>
    <span class="n">dmg_ji</span> <span class="o">*=</span> <span class="nb">float</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">poke_row_j</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;attack&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="nb">float</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">poke_row_i</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;defence&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>
    <span class="n">dmg_ji</span> <span class="o">*=</span> <span class="n">weakness_weight</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">eval</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">poke_row_j</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;type&#39;</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="nb">eval</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">poke_row_i</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;type&#39;</span><span class="p">]))</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">poke_row_i</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;hp&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">dmg_ji</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">sim_poke_battle</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">poke_i</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poke_j</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Simulate the outcome between two pokemon. Output: winner_name, loser_name.</span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">calc_tij</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">poke_i</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poke_j</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">calc_tij</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">poke_j</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poke_i</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">poke_i</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poke_j</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">poke_j</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poke_i</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Let-it-run-here">Let it run here<a class="anchor-link" href="#Let-it-run-here"></a></h1>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">d</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">{}</span> 
<span class="n">poke_names</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span> <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">poke_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;name&#39;</span><span class="p">]]</span>

<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">_</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">poke_names</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">p1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">p2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">poke_names</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">_</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">poke_names</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">_</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span> 
    <span class="n">win</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lose</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sim_poke_battle</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">p2</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">update</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">win</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lose</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># this takes a while! </span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">_</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">50000</span><span class="p">):</span> 
    <span class="n">i</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">j</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">choice</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">poke_names</span><span class="p">)),</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">p1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">p2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">poke_names</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">poke_names</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">j</span><span class="p">]</span> 
    <span class="n">win</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lose</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sim_poke_battle</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">p2</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">update</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">win</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lose</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This takes a while, but when it is done we can create the same distribution chart as before but now for pokemon.</p>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Let's summarise the distributions and put them in a dataframe.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">scores</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span> 
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">poke</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">poke_names</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="n">scores</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="n">poke</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">d</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">poke</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">SIZE_ARR</span><span class="p">))])</span>
<span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">scores</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;name&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;mle&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now that we have some results, lets look at the top performing and the bottom performning pokemon.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="k">print</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;mle&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="k">print</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;mle&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tail</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<p>I have run this algorithm a few times and it seems doesn't seem to converge very consistently. It does some things very well; the fact that magicarp is generally performing poorly is good news. I've also noticed Mew/Mewtwo in the higher skilled area. I'm still conserned that this algorithm fails to grasp the rock/paper scissors element that is in the game. But the fact that I am assuming that every pokemon is fighting with only basic attacks also does not help.</p>
<p>As a final push one might consider making an ensemble of these pokemon rankings to see if the convergence can be make to go faster. Another tweak to consider is to have the matching of these pokemon not be random during the learning. I like the results of the exercize, but it seems that we are not done with ranking pokemon.</p>
